metaclass.name: MetaAttribute
metaclass.description: A metaattribute is a feature within a metaclass that describes a range of values that instances of the metaclass may hold. A metaattribute is a characteristic that describes an object or a link. Examples: The Flow-Type characteristic of a Message allows you to specify whether this Message is information, or a material or financial flow. The Predicate characteristic of the Send link between Message and Org-Unit allows you to specify the condition for sending the Message.

This alias is a shortname used for display.Possible value : string [0-20] characters.Do not set a value for this property if you are not an expert.

properties.name: MetaAttributeType

Value must belong to [0-1024]  	VarChar: A. ANSI. Use it for large texts like comments 	Datetime: D. Use it for dates 	Boolean: 1. Values are 0 or 1. Not recommended. Use rather String with a tabulated values 	Short: S. Use it for small numbers if you compute data. Value must belong to [0-65535] 	Double: H. Use it for numbers if you compute data. Value must belong to [0-18446744073709551616] 	Long: L. Value must belong to [0-4294967295] 	Float: F. Use it for large numbers if you compute data.  	Binary: Q. Internal. Do not use it 	VarBinary: B. Internal. Do not use itNote: the internal format of date is  YYYY MM DD HH:MM:SS

properties.name: Loggability
properties.description: This parameter defines for a MetaObject if updates will be logged in the transaction embedded logfile or not.Do not set a value for this property if you are not an expert. Possible values:?	Unloggable: U: updates are not logged (Be careful, your updates are also not dispatched !)?	Loggable     : L (default): updates are logged. Attention: this is an expert customization :1) A specific study should be made to evaluate the specific impacts of this change.MEGA is not commited to perform this study. It is the project responsibility.This change will not remove data from the existing logfile (object dispatched and logged before the change).2) To perform this change the user must be allowed to update MEGA data.A metamodel compilation must be performed to validate the change.3) Platform technical impactsIf data a regularily created for this MetaClass and if repository logfile is enabled-Repository size will increase more slowly. -Transaction dispatch performances will improve.4) Platform functional impactsFor each Metaclass where logging has been disabled, the following features will not be available:-Export of repository logfile from the Administration Console does not contain updates for this MetaClass. -Transaction backup logfile (external file) does not contain updates for this MetaClass. -View object history (tab General > History of objects) does not display updates for this MetaClass. -View object history (Menu File > Properties, tab  Updates ) does not display updates for this MetaClass. -Undo redo is not available for updates regarding this MetaClass. -In the window displayed when exiting MEGA, the button  Later  is not displayed if all updates are regarding this MetaClass?

properties.name: MetaLayer
properties.description: This parameter indicates if an object belongs to the metamodel layer or to the meta-metamodel layer of the MOF (Meta Object facility) architecture.Do not set a value for this property if you are not an expert.The MEGA Software environment is based on a four-layer architecture as standardized by the OMG:- M0: The information layer comprises data of the  real world  which the user describes using MEGA products. (e.g.  Alan Smith )- M1: The model layer comprises models that describe data in the information layer. Since MEGA software is a true modeling environment, we can say that this is the  MEGA world  (e.g.  Sales Director )- M2: The metamodel layer comprises several domain-specific metamodels. A metamodel is an  abstract language  defined to write models. A set of concepts relating to the domain being modeled. MEGA products provide an extensive collection of such metamodels, for example the UML metamodel, the workflow (BPMN) metamodel and the business process metamodel. These metamodels can be modified or extended to suit specific requirements.  Metamodel  is the default value and should be used for extensions. (e.g.  Org-Unit )- M3: The meta-metamodel layer comprises the  top level  metamodel required to describe any type of metamodel. The MEGA meta-metamodel complies with the MOF (Meta Object Facility) recommendations of the OMG. It is reflexive, i.e. able to define itself as well as any type of metamodel. MOF is a very high level standardized metamodel, modification of which we do not recommend. Conventionally, meta-meta-objects are prefixed  Meta . (e.g.  MetaClass )

metaclass.description: A metaclass is a class whose instances are classes. Metaclasses are typically used to construct metamodels. Metaclasses are used in the explorer when searching for objects in the repository and when the metamodel is extended to include a new type of object. Example: message, org-unit, etc.

properties.name: Loggability
properties.description: This parameter defines for a MetaObject if updates will be logged in the transaction embedded logfile or not.Do not set a value for this property if you are not an expert. Possible values:?	Unloggable: U: updates are not logged (Be careful, your updates are also not dispatched !)?	Loggable     : L (default): updates are logged. Attention: this is an expert customization :1) A specific study should be made to evaluate the specific impacts of this change.MEGA is not commited to perform this study. It is the project responsibility.This change will not remove data from the existing logfile (object dispatched and logged before the change).2) To perform this change the user must be allowed to update MEGA data.A metamodel compilation must be performed to validate the change.3) Platform technical impactsIf data a regularily created for this MetaClass and if repository logfile is enabled-Repository size will increase more slowly. -Transaction dispatch performances will improve.4) Platform functional impactsFor each Metaclass where logging has been disabled, the following features will not be available:-Export of repository logfile from the Administration Console does not contain updates for this MetaClass. -Transaction backup logfile (external file) does not contain updates for this MetaClass. -View object history (tab General > History of objects) does not display updates for this MetaClass. -View object history (Menu File > Properties, tab  Updates ) does not display updates for this MetaClass. -Undo redo is not available for updates regarding this MetaClass. -In the window displayed when exiting MEGA, the button  Later  is not displayed if all updates are regarding this MetaClass?

properties.name: MetaLayer
properties.description: This parameter indicates if an object belongs to the metamodel layer or to the meta-metamodel layer of the MOF (Meta Object facility) architecture.Do not set a value for this property if you are not an expert.The MEGA Software environment is based on a four-layer architecture as standardized by the OMG:- M0: The information layer comprises data of the  real world  which the user describes using MEGA products. (e.g.  Alan Smith )- M1: The model layer comprises models that describe data in the information layer. Since MEGA software is a true modeling environment, we can say that this is the  MEGA world  (e.g.  Sales Director )- M2: The metamodel layer comprises several domain-specific metamodels. A metamodel is an  abstract language  defined to write models. A set of concepts relating to the domain being modeled. MEGA products provide an extensive collection of such metamodels, for example the UML metamodel, the workflow (BPMN) metamodel and the business process metamodel. These metamodels can be modified or extended to suit specific requirements.  Metamodel  is the default value and should be used for extensions. (e.g.  Org-Unit )- M3: The meta-metamodel layer comprises the  top level  metamodel required to describe any type of metamodel. The MEGA meta-metamodel complies with the MOF (Meta Object Facility) recommendations of the OMG. It is reflexive, i.e. able to define itself as well as any type of metamodel. MOF is a very high level standardized metamodel, modification of which we do not recommend. Conventionally, meta-meta-objects are prefixed  Meta . (e.g.  MetaClass )

properties.name: MetaLayer
properties.description: This parameter indicates if an object belongs to the metamodel layer or to the meta-metamodel layer of the MOF (Meta Object facility) architecture.Do not set a value for this property if you are not an expert.The MEGA Software environment is based on a four-layer architecture as standardized by the OMG:- M0: The information layer comprises data of the  real world  which the user describes using MEGA products. (e.g.  Alan Smith )- M1: The model layer comprises models that describe data in the information layer. Since MEGA software is a true modeling environment, we can say that this is the  MEGA world  (e.g.  Sales Director )- M2: The metamodel layer comprises several domain-specific metamodels. A metamodel is an  abstract language  defined to write models. A set of concepts relating to the domain being modeled. MEGA products provide an extensive collection of such metamodels, for example the UML metamodel, the workflow (BPMN) metamodel and the business process metamodel. These metamodels can be modified or extended to suit specific requirements.  Metamodel  is the default value and should be used for extensions. (e.g.  Org-Unit )- M3: The meta-metamodel layer comprises the  top level  metamodel required to describe any type of metamodel. The MEGA meta-metamodel complies with the MOF (Meta Object Facility) recommendations of the OMG. It is reflexive, i.e. able to define itself as well as any type of metamodel. MOF is a very high level standardized metamodel, modification of which we do not recommend. Conventionally, meta-meta-objects are prefixed  Meta . (e.g.  MetaClass )

enumValues.name: TOGAFApplicationAndUserLocationDiagram_TAULD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Application and User Location Diagram - TOGAF Application and User Location DiagramThe Application and User Location diagram shows the geographical distribution of applications.It can be used to show where applications are used by the end user; the distribution of where the host application is executed and or delivered in thin client scenarios; the distribution of where applications are developed, tested, and released; etc.Analysis can reveal opportunities for rationalization, as well as duplication and or gaps.The purpose of this diagram is to clearly depict the business locations from which business users typically interact with the applications, but also the hosting location of the application infrastr ucture.The diagram enables:- Identification of the number of package instances needed to sufficiently support the user population that may be spread out geographically- Estimation of the number and the type of user licenses for the package or other software- Estimation of the level of support needed for the users and location of support center- Selection of system management tools, structure, and management system required to support the enterprise users customers partners both locally and remotely- Appropriate planning for the technological components of the business, namely server sizing and network bandwidth, etc.- Performance considerations while implementing application and technology architecture solutionsUsers typically interact with applications in a variety of ways; for example:- To support the operations of the business day-to-day- To participate in the execution of a business process- To access information (look-up, read)- To develop the application- To administer and maintain the application

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataMigrationDiagram_TDMD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Migration Diagram - TOGAF Data Migration DiagramData migration is critical when implementing a package or packaged service-based solution.This is particularly true when an existing legacy application is replaced with a package or an enterprise is to be migrated to a larger packages packaged services footprint. Packages tend to have their own data model and during data migration the legacy application data may need to be transformed pr ior to loading into the package.Data migration activities will usually involve the following steps:Extract data from source applications (baseline systems)- Profile source data- Perform data transformation operations, including data quality processes:  - Standardize, normalize, de-duplicate source data (data cleansing)  - Match, merge, and consolidate data from different source(s)  - Source-to-target mappings- Load into target applications (target systems)The purpose of the Data Migration diagram is to show the flow of data from the source to the target applications. The diagram will provide a visual representation of the spread of sources targets and serve as a tool for data auditing and establishing traceability. This diagram can be elaborated or enhanced as detailed as necessary. For example, the diagram can contain just an overall layout of migration landscape or could go into individual application metadata element level of detail.

enumValues.name: TOGAFProcessFlowDiagram_TPFD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Process Flow Diagram - TOGAF Process Flow DiagramThe purpose of the Process Flow diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to the process metamodel entity.Process Flow diagrams show sequential flow of control between activities and may utilize swimlane techniques to represent ownership and realization of process steps. For example, the application that supports a process step may be shown as a swim-lane.In addition to showing a sequence of activity, process flows can also be used to detail the controls that apply to a process, the events that trigger or result from completion of a process, and also the products that are generated from process execution.Process Flow diagrams are useful in elaborating the architecture with subject specialists, as they allow the specialist to describe  how the job is done  for a particular function. Through this process, each process step can become a more fine-grained function and can then in turn be elaborated as a process.

enumValues.name: ServiceArchitectureDiagram_SAD

enumValues.name: OverviewOfBusinessFunctions_BFMD
enumValues.description: Overview of Business Functions - Overview of Business FunctionsThis diagram presents an assessment of flows between the enterprise s main business functions.This assessment is made through the use of channels which list the flows exchanged between activities (involvement of business functions within business processes).

enumValues.name: TOGAFEnvironmentsAndLocationsDiagram_TELD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Environments and Locations Diagram - TOGAF Environments and Locations DiagramThe Environments and Locations diagram depicts which locations host which applications, identifies what technologies and or applications are used at which locations, and finally identifies the locations from which business users typically interact with the applications.This diagram should also show the existence and location of different deployment environments, including non-production environments, such as development and pre production.

enumValues.name: ResourceArchitectureTreeDiagram_CCTD

enumValues.name: EnterprisePhaseTreeDiagram_EPTD
enumValues.description: Enterprise Phase Tree Diagram - Enterprise Phase Tree DiagramAn Enterprise Phase Tree Diagram is a diagram showing the hierarchy of Enterprise Phase.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataLifecycleDiagram_TDLD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Lifecycle Diagram - TOGAF Data Lifecycle DiagramThe Data Lifecycle diagram is an essential part of managing business data throughout its lifecycle from conception until disposal within the constraints of the business process.The data is considered as an entity in its own right, decoupled from business process and activity. Each change in state is represented on the diagram which may include the event or rules that trigger that change in state.The separation of data from process allows common data requirements to be identified which enables resource sharing to be achieved more effectively.

enumValues.name: SystemProcessDiagram_BPMNSYSPROC
enumValues.description: System Process Diagram - System Process DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a system process using the BPMN notation. You can show the sequences of tasks, the conditioning and the events. Tasks can be assigned to participants that represent applications, IT services or org-units (for interactive tasks).This representation of a process is used to answer the question: how does my system work?

enumValues.name: ValueStreamDiagram_BPMNFUNPROC

You can show the sequences of Value Stages, the conditioning and the events. Value Stages can be assigned to participants that represent the skills needed to perform them.This representation of a Value Stream is used to respond to the question: which skill do I need?

enumValues.name: ClassDiagram_MOBJ

enumValues.name: TOGAFGoalObjectiveServiceDiagram_TGOSD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Goal/Objective/Service Diagram - TOGAF Goal/Objective/Service DiagramThe purpose of a Goal Objective Service diagram is to define the ways in which a service contributes to the achievement of a business vision or strategy.Services are associated with the drivers, goals, objectives, and measures that they support, allowing the enterprise to understand which services contribute to similar aspects of business performance. The Goal Objective Service diagram also provides qualitative input on what constitutes high performance for a particular service.

enumValues.name: StateDiagram_MTRE
enumValues.description: State Diagram - State DiagramA state diagram describes the evolution over time of an object of a certain class, and shows its behavior in response to interactions with other objects (internal or external to the studied system) in its environment.

enumValues.name: ApplicationStructureDiagram_ASD
enumValues.description: Application Structure Diagram - Application Structure DiagramAn Application Structure Diagram displays graphically the first level components of an Application, the access points (service request points) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataSecurityDiagram_TDSD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Security Diagram - TOGAF Data Security DiagramData is considered as an asset to the enterprise and data security simply means ensuring that enterprise data is not compromised and that access to it is suitably controlled.The purpose of the Data Security diagram is to depict which actor (person, organization, or system) can access which enterprise data. This relationship can be shown in a matrix form between two objects or can be shown as a mapping.The diagram can also be used to demonstrate compliance with data privacy laws and other applicable regulations (HIPAA, SOX, etc). This diagram should also consider any trust implications where an enterprise s partners or other parties may have access to the company s systems, such as an outsourced situation where information may be managed by other people and may even be hosted in a different country.

enumValues.name: OrganizationalChart_ORGANIGRAMME

enumValues.name: ApplicationArchitectureDiagram_MODELE_APPLICATION
enumValues.description: Application Architecture Diagram - Application Architecture DiagramAn Application Architecture Diagram describes the software environment of an application, a site, an org-unit, or for the entire company

enumValues.name: RelationalDiagram_MR
enumValues.description: Relational Diagram - Relational DiagramA relational diagram describes a database: It represents the physical data structures used by programs.

enumValues.name: UseCaseDiagram_MUTI
enumValues.description: Use Case Diagram - Use Case DiagramUse case diagrams show actors and use cases together with their relationships. The use cases represent functionality of a system as manifested to external interactors with the system or the classifier.

enumValues.name: TechnicalArchitectureDiagram_MAT
enumValues.description: Technical Architecture Diagram - Technical Architecture DiagramThe Technical Architecture Diagram (TAD) focuses on the hardware architecture needed to run the software. This type of diagram provides a detailed description of the technical architecture: network management, information flows, routing, and so on.The TAD also allows you to choose the correct hardware configuration for your applications and databases, plus the networks used to exchange information.

enumValues.name: BusinessServiceTreeDiagram_BSTD

enumValues.name: BusinessFunctionalAreaDiagram_BF_ARC

enumValues.name: TOGAFPlatformDecompositionDiagram_TPDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Platform Decomposition Diagram - TOGAF Platform Decomposition DiagramThe Platform Decomposition diagram depicts the technology platform that supports the operations of the Information Systems Architecture. The diagram covers all aspects of the infrastructure platform and provides an overview of the enterprise s technology platform. The diagram can be expanded to map the technology platform to appropriate application components within a specific functional or process area. This diagram may show details of specification, such as product versions, number of CPUs, etc. or simply could be an informal  eye-chart  providing an overview of the technical environment.

enumValues.name: CommunicationDiagram_COMMUNICATION
enumValues.description: Communication Diagram - Communication Diagram (UML2)Communication Diagrams focus on the interaction between lifelines where the architecture of the internal structure and how this corresponds with the message passing is central. The sequencing of messages is given through a sequence numbering scheme.The communication diagram is a simplified representation of the sequence diagram, concentrating on message exchanges between objects within an interaction.

enumValues.name: ActivityDiagramUMLTwo_ACTIVIYYDIAGUMLTwo
enumValues.description: Activity Diagram (UML2) - Activity Diagram (UML2)An activity diagram describes the sequence and conditions coordinating actions as well as the object flows exchanged during processing.These actions can be initiated because other actions finish executing, because objects and data become available, or because events occur external to the flow.

enumValues.name: InteractionOverviewDiagram_InteractionOverview
enumValues.description: Interaction Overview Diagram - Interaction Overview Diagram (UML2)Interaction Overview Diagrams define interactions through a variant of activity diagrams in a way that promotes overview of the control flow. They focus on the overview of the flow of control where the nodes are interactions or  interaction uses. The interaction overview diagram describes sequences possible between scenarios previously identified in the form of sequence diagrams.

enumValues.name: LogicalApplicationSystemEnvironmentDiagram_LASE
enumValues.description: Logical Application System Environment Diagram - SOIA - Logical Application System EnvironmentA Logical Application System Environment Diagram describes the interactions between a logical application system and its external partners in a specific context.

enumValues.name: Org_UnitOrganizationalChart_ORGUNITORGCHART
enumValues.description: Org-Unit Organizational Chart - Org-Unit Organizational ChartThis diagram provides the description of the org-unit structure.Both hierarchical and functional dependencies can be shown.

enumValues.name: TOGAFApplicationCommunicationDiagram_TACD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Application Communication Diagram - TOGAF Application Communication DiagramThe purpose of the Application Communication diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to communication between applications in the metamodel entity.It shows application components and interfaces between components. Interfaces may be associated with data entities where appropriate. Applications may be associated with business services where appropriate. Communication should be logical and should only show intermediary technology where it is architecturally relevant.

enumValues.name: TOGAFEventDiagram_TED
enumValues.description: TOGAF Event Diagram - TOGAF Event DiagramThe purpose of the Event diagram is to depict the relationship between events and process.Certain events - such as arrival of certain information (e.g., customer submits sales order) or a certain point in time (e.g., end of fiscal quarter) - cause work and certain actions need to be under taken within the business. These are often referred to as  business events  or simply  events  and are considered as triggers for a process. It is important to note that the event has to trigger a process and generate a business response or result.

enumValues.name: SystemProcessTreeDiagram_SYSPROC_TREE
enumValues.description: System Process Tree Diagram - System Process Tree DiagramA System Process Tree Diagram represents the hierarchical structure of  System Processs.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataDisseminationDiagram_TDDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Dissemination Diagram - TOGAF Data Dissemination DiagramThe purpose of the Data Dissemination diagram is to show the relationship between data entity, business service, and application components. The diagram shows how the logical entities are to be physically realized by application components. This allows effective sizing to be carried out and the IT footprint to be refined. Moreover, by assigning business value to data, an indication of the business criticality of application components can be gained.Additionally, the diagram may show data replication and system ownership of the master reference for data. In this instance, it can show two copies and the master-copy relationship between them. This diagram can include services; that is, services encapsulate data and they reside in an application, or services that reside on an application and access data encapsulated within the application.

enumValues.name: TOGAFFunctionalDecompositionDiagram_TFDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Functional Decomposition Diagram - TOGAF Functional Decomposition DiagramThe purpose of the Functional Decomposition diagram is to show on a single page the capabilities of an organization that are relevant to the consideration of an architecture. By examining the capabilities of an organization from a functional perspective, it is possible to quickly develop models of what the organization does without being dragged into extended debate on how the organization does it.Once a basic Functional Decomposition diagram has been developed, it becomes possible to layer heat-maps on top of this diagram to show scope and decisions. For example, thecapabilities to be implemented in different phases of a change program.

enumValues.description: TOGAF Application and User Location Diagram - TOGAF Application and User Location DiagramThe Application and User Location diagram shows the geographical distribution of applications.It can be used to show where applications are used by the end user; the distribution of where the host application is executed and or delivered in thin client scenarios; the distribution of where applications are developed, tested, and released; etc.Analysis can reveal opportunities for rationalization, as well as duplication and or gaps.The purpose of this diagram is to clearly depict the business locations from which business users typically interact with the applications, but also the hosting location of the application infrastr ucture.The diagram enables:- Identification of the number of package instances needed to sufficiently support the user population that may be spread out geographically- Estimation of the number and the type of user licenses for the package or other software- Estimation of the level of support needed for the users and location of support center- Selection of system management tools, structure, and management system required to support the enterprise users customers partners both locally and remotely- Appropriate planning for the technological components of the business, namely server sizing and network bandwidth, etc.- Performance considerations while implementing application and technology architecture solutionsUsers typically interact with applications in a variety of ways; for example:- To support the operations of the business day-to-day- To participate in the execution of a business process- To access information (look-up, read)- To develop the application- To administer and maintain the application

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataMigrationDiagram_TDMD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Migration Diagram - TOGAF Data Migration DiagramData migration is critical when implementing a package or packaged service-based solution.This is particularly true when an existing legacy application is replaced with a package or an enterprise is to be migrated to a larger packages packaged services footprint. Packages tend to have their own data model and during data migration the legacy application data may need to be transformed pr ior to loading into the package.Data migration activities will usually involve the following steps:Extract data from source applications (baseline systems)- Profile source data- Perform data transformation operations, including data quality processes:  - Standardize, normalize, de-duplicate source data (data cleansing)  - Match, merge, and consolidate data from different source(s)  - Source-to-target mappings- Load into target applications (target systems)The purpose of the Data Migration diagram is to show the flow of data from the source to the target applications. The diagram will provide a visual representation of the spread of sources targets and serve as a tool for data auditing and establishing traceability. This diagram can be elaborated or enhanced as detailed as necessary. For example, the diagram can contain just an overall layout of migration landscape or could go into individual application metadata element level of detail.

enumValues.name: ApplicationSystemTechnicalArchitectureDiagram_ITARC_ASTA_TAD
enumValues.description: Application System Technical Architecture Diagram - IT Architecture - ASTA - Technical Architecture DiagramThis Technical Architecture diagram represents the Technical Architectures and the Technical Data Areas of the described Application System Technical Architecture as well as the techniques used for their communications.

enumValues.name: EnterprisePhaseTreeDiagram_EPTD
enumValues.description: Enterprise Phase Tree Diagram - Enterprise Phase Tree DiagramAn Enterprise Phase Tree Diagram is a diagram showing the hierarchy of Enterprise Phase.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataLifecycleDiagram_TDLD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Lifecycle Diagram - TOGAF Data Lifecycle DiagramThe Data Lifecycle diagram is an essential part of managing business data throughout its lifecycle from conception until disposal within the constraints of the business process.The data is considered as an entity in its own right, decoupled from business process and activity. Each change in state is represented on the diagram which may include the event or rules that trigger that change in state.The separation of data from process allows common data requirements to be identified which enables resource sharing to be achieved more effectively.

enumValues.name: SystemProcessDiagram_BPMNSYSPROC
enumValues.description: System Process Diagram - System Process DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a system process using the BPMN notation. You can show the sequences of tasks, the conditioning and the events. Tasks can be assigned to participants that represent applications, IT services or org-units (for interactive tasks).This representation of a process is used to answer the question: how does my system work?

enumValues.name: GlobalApplicationFlowMap_GLOBINTSCEDIAG
enumValues.description: Global Application Flow Map - Global Application Flow Map

enumValues.name: ValueStreamDiagram_BPMNFUNPROC
enumValues.description: Value Stream Diagram - Functional Process DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a Value Stream, using the BPMN notation. You can show the sequences of Value Stages, the conditioning and the events. Value Stages can be assigned to participants that represent the skills needed to perform them.This representation of a Value Stream is used to respond to the question: which skill do I need?

enumValues.name: ScenarioOfApplicationFlowsDiagram_APPLIINTERSCENA
enumValues.description: Scenario of Application Flows Diagram - Scenario of Application Flows

enumValues.name: ClassDiagram_MOBJ
enumValues.description: Class Diagram - Class DiagramA class diagram is used to represent the static structure of a system, particularly the types of objects manipulated in the system, their internal structure, and the relationships between them.

enumValues.name: TOGAFGoalObjectiveServiceDiagram_TGOSD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Goal/Objective/Service Diagram - TOGAF Goal/Objective/Service DiagramThe purpose of a Goal Objective Service diagram is to define the ways in which a service contributes to the achievement of a business vision or strategy.Services are associated with the drivers, goals, objectives, and measures that they support, allowing the enterprise to understand which services contribute to similar aspects of business performance. The Goal Objective Service diagram also provides qualitative input on what constitutes high performance for a particular service.

enumValues.name: StateDiagram_MTRE
enumValues.description: State Diagram - State DiagramA state diagram describes the evolution over time of an object of a certain class, and shows its behavior in response to interactions with other objects (internal or external to the studied system) in its environment.

enumValues.name: ApplicationStructureDiagram_ASD
enumValues.description: Application Structure Diagram - Application Structure DiagramAn Application Structure Diagram displays graphically the first level components of an Application, the access points (service request points) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataSecurityDiagram_TDSD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Security Diagram - TOGAF Data Security DiagramData is considered as an asset to the enterprise and data security simply means ensuring that enterprise data is not compromised and that access to it is suitably controlled.The purpose of the Data Security diagram is to depict which actor (person, organization, or system) can access which enterprise data. This relationship can be shown in a matrix form between two objects or can be shown as a mapping.The diagram can also be used to demonstrate compliance with data privacy laws and other applicable regulations (HIPAA, SOX, etc). This diagram should also consider any trust implications where an enterprise s partners or other parties may have access to the company s systems, such as an outsourced situation where information may be managed by other people and may even be hosted in a different country.

enumValues.name: OrganizationalChart_ORGANIGRAMME
enumValues.description: Organizational Chart - Organizational ChartThis diagram provides the description of the org-unit structure.Both hierarchical and functional dependencies can be shown.

enumValues.name: ApplicationArchitectureDiagram_MODELE_APPLICATION
enumValues.description: Application Architecture Diagram - Application Architecture DiagramAn Application Architecture Diagram describes the software environment of an application, a site, an org-unit, or for the entire company

enumValues.name: RelationalDiagram_MR
enumValues.description: Relational Diagram - Relational DiagramA relational diagram describes a database: It represents the physical data structures used by programs.

enumValues.name: UseCaseDiagram_MUTI
enumValues.description: Use Case Diagram - Use Case DiagramUse case diagrams show actors and use cases together with their relationships. The use cases represent functionality of a system as manifested to external interactors with the system or the classifier.

enumValues.name: ApplicationTree_ARBRE_APPLICATIF
enumValues.description: Application Tree - Application Tree DiagramThis diagram describes an application through a tree diagram of its components (sub-applications and services).

enumValues.name: TechnicalArchitectureDiagram_MAT
enumValues.description: Technical Architecture Diagram - Technical Architecture DiagramThe Technical Architecture Diagram (TAD) focuses on the hardware architecture needed to run the software. This type of diagram provides a detailed description of the technical architecture: network management, information flows, routing, and so on.The TAD also allows you to choose the correct hardware configuration for your applications and databases, plus the networks used to exchange information.

enumValues.name: BusinessServiceTreeDiagram_BSTD
enumValues.description: Business Service Tree Diagram - Business Service Tree DiagramA Business Service Tree Diagram represents the hierarchical structure of Business Services.

enumValues.name: BusinessFunctionalAreaDiagram_BF_ARC
enumValues.description: Business Functional Area Diagram - BA - Business Functional Area Diagram

enumValues.name: TOGAFPlatformDecompositionDiagram_TPDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Platform Decomposition Diagram - TOGAF Platform Decomposition DiagramThe Platform Decomposition diagram depicts the technology platform that supports the operations of the Information Systems Architecture. The diagram covers all aspects of the infrastructure platform and provides an overview of the enterprise s technology platform. The diagram can be expanded to map the technology platform to appropriate application components within a specific functional or process area. This diagram may show details of specification, such as product versions, number of CPUs, etc. or simply could be an informal  eye-chart  providing an overview of the technical environment.

enumValues.name: CommunicationDiagram_COMMUNICATION
enumValues.description: Communication Diagram - Communication Diagram (UML2)Communication Diagrams focus on the interaction between lifelines where the architecture of the internal structure and how this corresponds with the message passing is central. The sequencing of messages is given through a sequence numbering scheme.The communication diagram is a simplified representation of the sequence diagram, concentrating on message exchanges between objects within an interaction.

enumValues.name: ActivityDiagramUMLTwo_ACTIVIYYDIAGUMLTwo
enumValues.description: Activity Diagram (UML2) - Activity Diagram (UML2)An activity diagram describes the sequence and conditions coordinating actions as well as the object flows exchanged during processing.These actions can be initiated because other actions finish executing, because objects and data become available, or because events occur external to the flow.

enumValues.name: InteractionOverviewDiagram_InteractionOverview
enumValues.description: Interaction Overview Diagram - Interaction Overview Diagram (UML2)Interaction Overview Diagrams define interactions through a variant of activity diagrams in a way that promotes overview of the control flow. They focus on the overview of the flow of control where the nodes are interactions or  interaction uses. The interaction overview diagram describes sequences possible between scenarios previously identified in the form of sequence diagrams.

enumValues.name: LogicalApplicationSystemEnvironmentDiagram_LASE
enumValues.description: Logical Application System Environment Diagram - SOIA - Logical Application System EnvironmentA Logical Application System Environment Diagram describes the interactions between a logical application system and its external partners in a specific context.

enumValues.name: Org_UnitOrganizationalChart_ORGUNITORGCHART
enumValues.description: Org-Unit Organizational Chart - Org-Unit Organizational ChartThis diagram provides the description of the org-unit structure.Both hierarchical and functional dependencies can be shown.

enumValues.name: TOGAFApplicationCommunicationDiagram_TACD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Application Communication Diagram - TOGAF Application Communication DiagramThe purpose of the Application Communication diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to communication between applications in the metamodel entity.It shows application components and interfaces between components. Interfaces may be associated with data entities where appropriate. Applications may be associated with business services where appropriate. Communication should be logical and should only show intermediary technology where it is architecturally relevant.

enumValues.name: TOGAFEventDiagram_TED
enumValues.description: TOGAF Event Diagram - TOGAF Event DiagramThe purpose of the Event diagram is to depict the relationship between events and process.Certain events - such as arrival of certain information (e.g., customer submits sales order) or a certain point in time (e.g., end of fiscal quarter) - cause work and certain actions need to be under taken within the business. These are often referred to as  business events  or simply  events  and are considered as triggers for a process. It is important to note that the event has to trigger a process and generate a business response or result.

enumValues.name: SystemProcessTreeDiagram_SYSPROC_TREE
enumValues.description: System Process Tree Diagram - System Process Tree DiagramA System Process Tree Diagram represents the hierarchical structure of  System Processs.

enumValues.name: TOGAFDataDisseminationDiagram_TDDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Data Dissemination Diagram - TOGAF Data Dissemination DiagramThe purpose of the Data Dissemination diagram is to show the relationship between data entity, business service, and application components. The diagram shows how the logical entities are to be physically realized by application components. This allows effective sizing to be carried out and the IT footprint to be refined. Moreover, by assigning business value to data, an indication of the business criticality of application components can be gained.Additionally, the diagram may show data replication and system ownership of the master reference for data. In this instance, it can show two copies and the master-copy relationship between them. This diagram can include services; that is, services encapsulate data and they reside in an application, or services that reside on an application and access data encapsulated within the application.

enumValues.name: TOGAFFunctionalDecompositionDiagram_TFDD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Functional Decomposition Diagram - TOGAF Functional Decomposition DiagramThe purpose of the Functional Decomposition diagram is to show on a single page the capabilities of an organization that are relevant to the consideration of an architecture. By examining the capabilities of an organization from a functional perspective, it is possible to quickly develop models of what the organization does without being dragged into extended debate on how the organization does it.Once a basic Functional Decomposition diagram has been developed, it becomes possible to layer heat-maps on top of this diagram to show scope and decisions. For example, thecapabilities to be implemented in different phases of a change program.

enumValues.name: RiskDiagram_RISKD
enumValues.description: Risk Diagram - Risk DiagramThis diagram is used to describe where a risk can occur, its impacts and how it can be prevented.

enumValues.name: StateConceptStructureDiagram_SCPTINFODIAG
enumValues.description: State Concept Structure Diagram - State Concept StructureDiagramThis diagram is used to describe a concept state structure. It looks like a concept structure diagram.

enumValues.name: ServiceTaxonomyDiagram_SDVD
enumValues.description: Service Taxonomy Diagram - Service Taxonomy DiagramThis diagram describes the taxonomy of the service definition through a tree diagram of its specializations and generalizations.

enumValues.name: Cause_and_EffectDiagram_CED
enumValues.description: Cause-and-Effect Diagram - Causes/Effects DiagramThe cause-and-effect diagram (also called Ishikawa diagram or fishbone diagram) is a tool that enables identification of the possible causes of an observed effect and therefore determination of a means of solving the problems.

enumValues.name: GeneralOrganizationalChart_GENORGCHART
enumValues.description: General Organizational Chart - General Organizational ChartThis diagram provides a general description of the enterprise management structureIt enables description of both hierarchical and functional dependencies.

enumValues.name: TimelineDiagram_TIMELINE
enumValues.description: Timeline Diagram - Timeline DiagramThe Timeline diagram presents the sequance of key timespots of an organization or a project. A timespot can be represented by a fixed date or a limited time period.

enumValues.name: BusinessFunctionStructureDiagram_ONSD
enumValues.description: Business Function Structure Diagram - Operational Node Structure DiagramA Operational Node Structure Diagram displays graphically the first level components of a Business Function, the access points (service request points) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.name: OrganizationEnvironmentDiagram_ORGENVDIAG
enumValues.description: Organization Environment Diagram - Organization Environment Diagram

enumValues.name: TOGAFEnterpriseManageabilityDiagram_TEMD
enumValues.description: TOGAF Enterprise Manageability Diagram - TOGAF Enterprise Manageability DiagramThe Enterprise Manageability diagram shows how one or more applications interact with application and technology components that support operational management of a solution.This diagram is really a filter on the Application Communication diagram, specifically for enterprise management class software.Analysis can reveal duplication and gaps, and opportunities in the IT service management operation of an organization.

enumValues.name: PackageDiagram_MPAC
enumValues.description: Package Diagram - Package DiagramA package diagram divides the classes into different packages, in order to partition the work involved in specification and development. A class should only appear in a single package. Dividing into packages is generally carried out so as to minimise interactions between different packages.

enumValues.name: IDEFDataAreaDiagram_IDEFDAD
enumValues.description: IDEF Data Area Diagram - IDEF Data Area Diagram

enumValues.name: TOGAFCommunicationsEngineeringDiagram_TCED
enumValues.description: TOGAF Communications Engineering Diagram - TOGAF Communications Engineering DiagramThe purpose of the Application Communication diagram is to depict all models and mappings related to communication between applications in the metamodel entity.It shows application components and interfaces between components. Interfaces may be associated with data entities where appropriate. Applications may be associated with business services where appropriate. Communication should be logical and should only show intermediary technology where it is architecturally relevant.

enumValues.name: ApplicationSystemEnvironmentScenario_APPSYSENVINTSCENARIO
enumValues.description: Application System Environment Scenario - Application System Environment Scenario

enumValues.name: LogicalApplicationSystemStructureDiagram_SSASD
enumValues.description: Logical Application System Structure Diagram - Logical Application System Structure DiagramDiagram describing the internal structure of a Logical Application System, its provided or requested services, its conducted processes, its components and their interactions as well as end-users and their interactions with components.

enumValues.name: TechnicalFunctionalityDiagram_TECHFUNCTD
enumValues.description: Technical Functionality Diagram - Technical Functionality DiagramA Technical Functionality Diagram is a representation of the set of functionalities with their dependencies that, jointly, define the scope of an equipment item (hardware or software) corresponding to the Technical Functionality.

enumValues.name: TechnicalFunctionalityMapDiagram_TECHFUNCTMD
enumValues.description: Technical Functionality Map Diagram - Technical Functionality Map DiagramA Technical Functionality Map Diagram is a representation of the set of functionalities with their dependencies that, jointly, define the scope of an equipment item (hardware or software) corresponding to the Technical Functionality Map.

enumValues.name: UserInterfaceDiagram_UI
enumValues.description: User Interface Diagram - User Interface DiagramThe user interface diagram allows you to draw the graphical  interface of an interactive service or of a workflow operation.

enumValues.name: BusinessProcessDiagram_BPMNBIZPROC
enumValues.description: Business Process Diagram - Business Process Diagram (BPMN)This diagram is used to describe a structure of the business of the company. It presents product or service offerings, the composition of business processes that produce them and their implementation by functional, organizational or system processes. This diagram uses a subset of the BPMN notation.

enumValues.name: ProjectCompositionDiagram_PROJ_C
enumValues.description: Project Composition Diagram - Project Composition DiagramA Project Composition Diagram displays graphically the first level components of a EA Project.

enumValues.description: Application Environment Scenario Sequence Diagram - Application Environment Scenario Sequence Diagram

enumValues.description: Artifact Assembly Diagram - Artifact Assembly DiagramAn Artifact Assembly Diagram displays graphically the first level components of an Artifact, the access points (service request points, communication ports) and the connections between the components.

enumValues.description: Infrastructure Assembly Structure Diagram - IT Infrastructure Structure Diagram

enumValues.description: Business Function Hierarchy Diagram - Business Function Hierarchy DiagramThis diagram describes a business function through a tree diagram of its components.

enumValues.description: Interaction Scenario Diagram - Application Interaction Scenario DiagramThis diagram is used to describe a scenario enabling determination of interactions between sub-applications or services required to implement a use case of an application.

This string is computed using the date and time the session was opened, the number of objects created since the session started, and the object creation date (in milliseconds). An absolute identifier provides a unique way to identify an object in the repository, so that even if the object is renamed, all the links to it are retained.
